==Reception== {{update|section|reason=reviews and coverage of later series|date=August 2017}} Describing the outcome of the first episode of series one as a "scandal", Sam Wollaston writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' found the programme "incredibly interesting" and praised it "for being about just one case in which you can become totally involved, instead of flitting between three, which is what so many documentaries seem to do".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wollaston|first=Sam|title=TV review: ''Fake or Fortune?''; ''The Marriage Ref''|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/19/tv-review-fake-or-fortune|accessdate=25 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 June 2011}}</ref> In ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', Ceri Radford was described as being "flabbergasted" at the result of the first episode, but concluded her review by saying: "This may have been a disappointing finale, but it at least confirmed that this aesthetically pleasing, quietly enjoyable new series isn't afraid to thwart expectations."<ref name="Radford" /> [[Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)|Tom Sutcliffe]] in ''[[The Independent]]'' had a mixed view as a result of the presentation of the facts, saying: "It was full of cliffhanger tension and thrilling moments of discovery. But I couldn't entirely shift the suspicion that some of it was just a little too good to be true."<ref>{{cite news|last=Sutcliffe|first=Tom|title=The Weekend's TV: ''Fake or Fortune?'' Sun, BBC1 ''The Marriage Ref'', Sat, ITV1|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-tv-fake-or-fortune-sun-bbc1brthe-marriage-ref-sat-itv1-2299888.html|accessdate=25 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=20 June 2011|authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)}}</ref>
The first programme of the third series, shown in the UK on 19 January 2014, had 4.8 million viewers (a 21.8% audience share)<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|title=Call the Midwife attracts record audience on BBC1 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/20/call-the-midwife-bbc1 |accessdate=24 January 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 January 2014 }}</ref> while the first programme of the fourth series attracted 4.85m (24.5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a656650/uk-tv-ratings-sheridan-smiths-black-work-concludes-with-51m-on-itv.html#~pijiFtPoG7jbYd|title=UK TV ratings: Black Work concludes with 5.1m|date=6 July 2015|website=Digitalspy.co.uk|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>
The record audience for the series was on 12 July 2015 with a peak attendance of 5.8 million viewers (episode 4.2 "Renoir").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/3487_'Fake_or_Fortune?'|title='Fake or Fortune?' - Art History News - by Bendor Grosvenor|website=Arthistorynews.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>
Reviewing an episode of the seventh season, Michael Hogan of The Telegraph wrote "Arts programming is an increasingly endangered beast on prime time television. This absorbing and enjoyable series flies the flag in quietly thrilling fashion."<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/08/26/fake-fortune-episode-3-review-story-ended-infist-clenching-delight/ {{paywall}}</ref>
